[2]
Date: Mon 24 Jul 2006
From: Joe Dudley <jdudley@eaicorp.com>
Source: Reuters Alertnet, 24 Jul 2006 [edited]
<http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/BKK302025.htm>

Thailand finds bird flu, testing for H5N1
-----------------------------------------------
A strain of bird flu has been found in chickens in Thailand, and it
may prove to be the deadly H5N1 virus, senior Agriculture Ministry
official Yukol Limlaemthong said on Monday [24 Jul 2006].
"There is a high possibility it is the N1 strain, given that the area
has had outbreaks before," Yukol told Reuters.
Officials said the H5 virus was detected on a farm in the northern
province of Pichit, one of 7 "red zone" provinces where surveillance
was stepped up this month [July 2006], and test results were expected
in a few days.
If H5N1 is confirmed, it would be Thailand's 1st confirmed outbreak
of the virus in nearly 9 months.
Livestock officials culled all chickens in the affected area and
restricted poultry movements within a 10-km (6-mile) radius for at
least 30 days.
The H5N1 virus has killed 14 Thais since it 1st arrived in the
country in late 2003. The last death occurred in December 2005.
An 11-year-old girl was in a Pichit hospital on Monday [24 Jul 2006]
with flu-like symptoms, after chickens died on her family farm, a
doctor told Reuters. Test results are due on Tuesday [25 Jul 2006].
"The chickens started to die on 8 Jul 2006, and she helped her mother
bury the dead chickens without any protective gear," said Sunee
Thirakaroonwongse of the Pichit Provincial Hospital.
Thailand was slow to respond to bird flu when it began ravaging
poultry flocks in late 2003, but it now has one of the strongest
surveillance systems in the region.
However, recent incidents in which villagers have ignored government
warnings and handled dead chickens have raised fears that public
vigilance against the disease is waning.
The global human death toll is now at least 132 since the virus
reemerged in east Asia in 2003.
--
