[3]
Date: Mon 24 Jul 2006
From: Joe Dudley <jdudley@eaicorp.com>
Source: TNA via Etna.mcot.net, 24 Jul 2006 [edited]
<http://etna.mcot.net/query.php?nid=23580>

Thailand bans poultry imports to prevent new bird flu outbreak
-----------------------------------------------
Thailand has banned poultry imports from neighboring countries to
prevent a new outbreak of bird flu.
Agriculture and Cooperatives Minister Khunying Sudarat Keyuraphan
said on Monday [24 Jul 2006] that the ministry had ordered a total
ban on importing poultry from any neighboring country to prevent the
outbreak of bird flu.
The ban was imposed after some neighboring countries sent dead fowl
samples for laboratory tests in Thailand and some samples tested
positive for the virus.
Khunying Sudarat affirmed that no outbreak had been reported in areas
where many fowl died of unknown causes, and some weakened and became
vulnerable to bird flu virus. The minister, however, admitted the
presence of bird flu after an absence of nearly a year.
Khunying Sudarat announced that tests conducted on samples of dead
fighting cocks and domestic fowl in Bangmoonnak District of the
northern Phichit Province were positive. The laboratory technicians
have not yet been able to identify which strain it is. The fighting
cocks and domestic fowl sickened and died. The lab test showed that
they died of bird flu after Thailand had not confirmed the presence
of avian influenza for 254 days.
The Department of Livestock Development culled the remaining 260
chickens at the site and banned the movement of poultry within a 10-km radius.
Until now, there has been no report of bird flu patients in the area
where the chickens died.
Avian influenza outbreaks occurred in 14 locations in Phichit in 2004
and 3 locations last year [2005].
Meanwhile, Thailand's public health establishment breathed a
collective sigh of relief Monday [24 Jul 2006] as laboratory tests
confirmed that no new cases of H5N1 bird flu virus have been
transmitted to humans in recent months. [However, a suspected case is
mentioned in the 1st item above. - Mod.AS]
No deaths have occurred since February last year [2005], and no new
human bird flu cases have been found in Thailand over the past year
and a half, a senior Public Health Ministry official confirmed here
Monday [24 Jul 2006].
Director-General of the Department of Disease Control Dr. Thawat
Suntrajarn said, according to laboratory tests, patients who were
previously reported to have bird flu-like symptoms in many provinces
had all been proven to be bird-flu free.
"The patients, including 2 men in Phichit, were all found not having
contracted avian flu, but a strain of human influenza," he told journalists.
Dr. Thawat said, however, that more public health workers would be
sent to Phichit to help control the situation, following an official
report from the Department of Livestock Development that chickens in
Bangmoonnak District were found to have contracted the H5N1 virus.
--
Joseph P. Dudley, Ph.D.
Chief Scientist,
EAI Corporation
Arlington, VA 22203
<jdudley@eai.com>
[Thailand's official alert message to the OIE regarding an outbreak
of HPAI caused by an H5 virus in Bangmulnarg district (Pichit
province), was sent on 24 Jul 2006; see
<http://www.oie.int/Messages/060724THA.htm>.
Reportedly, the outbreak was found during the 2nd active surveillance
program for 2006, in progress since 1 Jun 2006 in high risk areas.
The previous outbreak of HPAI in poultry in Thailand was reported to
the OIE in November 2005.
ProMED-mail has been repeatedly reporting about mortalities in Thai
poultry, allegedly caused by fowl cholera, since 4 Jul 2006. In view
of the doubtful diagnosis, these postings were titled "undiagnosed
deaths," and information was requested, with special reference to
HPAI. The course of the current outbreak seems to be reminiscent of
the history of H5N1 diagnosis/reporting in Thailand in December
2003/January 2004 (see references).
Final confirmation of the causative agent by a reference laboratory
is anticipated. - Mod.AS]
